node.text:
Diversity holds many definitions that encompass a broad range of categories and topics that mean something different to everyone—so we asked members of our BIPOC & Allies Associate Resource Group what diversity personally means to them. 

“To me personally, what diversity means is really anything outside of my individual bubble that challenges me to think differently, look at situations differently—look at people, places and things in a different context.” - Claudette Hunter 

As part of our A&F Conversations series, we’ve teamed up with our BIPOC & Allies Associate Resource Group—a dedicated team of Abercrombie associates—to highlight some of the impactful work they do each day to create a safe space to learn, connect and be seen. It’s the work they do each day outside the 9-to-5 that provide associates a better understanding of allyship and encouragement to keep having the difficult, but necessary, conversations. 

Check back for more from our four-part series with our ARG.

“We really want to focus on creating initiatives and implementing those initiatives to better support our BIPOC associates as well as our BIPOC consumers... it’s something we are super-passionate about.” – Sofa Bah
 
Meet Sofa and a couple other ARG Board Members, Claudette Hunter and Sara Mellon, and check back for more.

Log off, kick back and tune in as we chat with Yasmine Cheyenne (@yasminecheyenne), Wellness Expert & Writer, who gently reminds us that the value of our worth comes from within, and how we can continue advocating for ourselves. 

“Although it’s completely okay to have goals and want to meet these particular achievements, worthiness comes from within... when we measure our worth based on how we believe in ourselves, or how we feel internally, then we begin to decide that we're worthy because we're human." 

Pour yourself a cup and head to our IGTV to watch the full video. 🥰

Gilly Chan (@gilly.inc), Model & Mental Health Advocate, writes a letter to her younger self: a reflection on what it means to be a black woman in a world that is finally starting to see her, and with the powerful affirmation that she was—and always will be—more than enough. 💌 
 
“To my younger self: I know this time feels really difficult. Right now, we feel lost and othered in our young body and mind; living in the confusion between who we are and who we think we should be... this society wasn’t built for our brown body. I see you—you aren’t invisible.” 
 
Head to our IGTV to watch the full video. ❤️

We’re so excited to have Gabby Royal (she/her/hers), our amazing Director of Global Diversity & Inclusion, on this episode of A&F Conversations. We sit down with Gabby to talk allyship development and how we can move from having conversations toward actual, tangible action—because investigating and interrupting our own unconscious biases is one of the most important efforts we can make to create change in our communities:

“In an effort to move from just discussions about diversity, inclusion and equity, we also have to acknowledge there are ways that we can hold ourselves accountable to do better and show up for communities who may hold identities that are different from the identities that we hold.” 

Head to our IGTV for the full conversation with Gabby.

Celebrate Native American Heritage Month with us—tune into our conversation with Artist & Influencer @notoriouscree, who discusses the practice of love from an indigenous perspective. 
 
“For a long time, I never loved myself. I looked in the mirror and saw somebody that I didn't love. But when I started to learn how to love that part of my journey, those things that were causing me not to love myself, I started to just be entrenched in that teaching. And it's helped me in so many ways.” 
 
Tune in to our IGTV for the full conversation with Notorious Cree.

"We are a happy people who are diverse and who are living full and fantastic lives, just like anybody else. We are healing en masse from the colonialism and traumatic history that we have experienced and we've been recovering from that for a very long time. 

Fortunately, we’ve carried our ancestral wellness practices with us and we are not only practicing again within our own communities, but we are now finding ways to share those with the rest of the world.” - @chelsey.moves 

Chelsey Luger, Indigenous Wellness Advocate & Co-Founder of @wellforculture, invites us to learn more about native culture and its ancestral wellness practices that we can incorporate into our lives. 

Join us in celebrating Native American Heritage month and be sure to check out our IGTV for the full conversation with Chelsey.

Head to our IGTV for the full conversation with Laith.

"I love creating work that puts Black joy on display. I believe it serves as a reminder to the viewer that our narrative—our experience in this life—does not only consist of our pain, trauma, and our will to fight back. There is more to our story..." - Francesca Miller (she/her), @_callmefree 🎨

Check out our latest For Justice, For Joy capsule co-created with visual artist Francesca Miller, that celebrates Black joy and what that means right now. 

On behalf of the Abercrombie Equity Project’s commitment to racial justice, we’re donating an additional $35,000* to the Steve Fund, the nation’s leading non-profit organization specifically dedicated to the mental health and emotional well-being of young people of color.
